"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896424","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-09","<p>The volumes of disposal types at the mandatory reconsideration stage broken down by month for Personal Independence Payment can be found in Table 7b of the quarterly bulletin “Personal Independence Payment: April 2013 to January 2018”.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-january-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-january-2018</a></p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-05-09T14:09:28.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896424/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896424/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896424/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-02","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of mandatory reconsiderations have upheld the original decision on personal independence payment in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Matt Western","Warwick and Leamington","Matt Western","140847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896425","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-14","<p>We will be publishing the zero emission road transport strategy shortly.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-05-14T14:22:06.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896425/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896425/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896425/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-02","Motor Vehicles: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the Government has set a publication date for the Pathway to Zero Emission Road Transport Strategy document.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","140537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896426","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-09","<p>The number of Mandatory Reconsiderations for Employment Support Allowance (ESA), by decision type, can be found in the official published statistics: “ESA: outcomes of Work Capability Assessments including mandatory reconsiderations and appeals: March 2018”. The relevant data can be found in Table 14.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/esa-outcomes-of-work-capability-assessments-including-mandatory-reconsiderations-and-appeals-march-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/esa-outcomes-of-work-capability-assessments-including-mandatory-reconsiderations-and-appeals-march-2018</a></p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-05-09T14:09:26.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896426/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896426/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896426/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-02","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of mandatory reconsiderations have upheld the original decision on employment support allowance in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Matt Western","Warwick and Leamington","Matt Western","140848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896427","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-05-09","<p>Information about the number and outcomes of Social Security and Child Support appeals by benefit type, including PIP, is published on gov.uk.</p><p> </p><p>The most recent statistics, for the period October to December 2017 (which includes data from the previous three years), published on 8 March, can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-2017" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-2017</a></p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-05-09T17:00:29.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896427/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896427/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896427/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-02","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of personal independence payment appeals have been successful at Tribunal in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Matt Western","Warwick and Leamington","Matt Western","140849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896428","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-14","<p>The Government does not hold information on the number of cars sold in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>However, the Department does have information on the number of cars registered for the first time in the UK in 2017 and 2016 from the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA). The following table includes the number of cars registered for the first time in the requested categories:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>(i) 2017</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>(ii) 2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>(a) Diesel</strong></p></td><td><p>1,047,446</p></td><td><p>1,262,167</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>(b) Petrol</strong></p></td><td><p>1,342,166</p></td><td><p>1,313,365</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>(c) Hybrid power</strong></p></td><td><p>100,642</p></td><td><p>78,667</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>(d) Electric power</strong></p></td><td><p>19,024</p></td><td><p>10,998</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-05-14T14:28:16.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896428/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896428/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896428/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-02","Cars: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate his Department has made of the number of cars which use (a) diesel, (b) petrol, (c) hybrid power and (d) electric power which were sold in the UK in (i) 2017 and (ii) 2016.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","140854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896429","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-05-14","<p>According to Sport England's most recent Active Lives Survey, around 77,500 people regularly play volleyball.</p><p>Sport England will be investing exchequer and lottery funding of almost £1.7m into Volleyball England to support its participation and talent programmes for the five-year period from 2017.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-05-14T12:49:18.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896429/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896429/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896429/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-05-02","Volleyball","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to encourage the take-up of volleyball in the UK.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","140855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896430","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-05-11","<p>Grassroots sports clubs can achieve status comparable to charitable status through the existing Community Amateur Sports Clubs (CASCs) scheme.</p><p> </p><p>If a sports club is eligible, and achieves CASC status it would receive tax relief on income, gains and profits from some activities, Gift Aid repayments on donations and business rates relief. For more information on CASCs, grass-roots sports clubs can visit the Sport England website.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-05-11T12:11:25.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896430/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896430/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896430/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-05-02","Sports: Charities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of bringing forward legislative proposals to grant charitable status to grass-root sports clubs.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","140856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896431","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-10","<p>In order to answer the question it would require a significant amount of new analysis to interrogate the Mental Health Services Data Set. NHS Digital has determined the cost of answering the Question to be approximately £2,854, consisting of £2,650 for the cost of producing the analysis, checking and formatting the reply, and £204 for the cost of manager validation and internal clearances.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-05-10T14:28:20.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896431/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896431/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-02","Compulsorily Detained Psychiatric Patients","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 2 May 2018 to Question 138009, what estimate he has made of the cost of answering that Question; and if he will publish a breakdown of those costs.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","140692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896432","Cabinet Office","false","2018-05-11","<p>It has been the policy of successive Governments not to comment on security matters other than in exceptional circumstances when it is in the public interest to do so.</p><p>The leak of any Government information or material is not acceptable and the Government takes such incidents very seriously.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2018-05-11T15:32:24.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896432/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896432/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-05-02","Cabinet Office: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many leak enquiries his Department has undertaken in the last two years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","140578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896433","Attorney General","false","2018-05-16","<p>It has been the policy of successive Governments not to comment on security matters other than in exceptional circumstances when it is in the public interest to do so.</p><p> </p><p>The leak of any Government information or material is not acceptable and the Government takes such incidents very seriously.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2018-05-16T10:44:19.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896433/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896433/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2018-05-02","Attorney General: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many leak enquiries his Department has undertaken in the last two years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","140579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896434","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-09","<p>Public Health England will contact all the women affected living within the United Kingdom who are registered with a general practitioner before the end of May with the first 65,000 letters going out last week. All reasonable efforts will be made to find the remainder who have moved from England. Any woman who thinks she may be affected has access to a helpline through which they can get access to clinical advice to help them decide whether or not a screening is appropriate for their particular situation.</p><p> </p><p>Data on the number of women affected will be published by the end of May.</p><p> </p><p>There has been no modelling done on the number of women estimated to have undetected breast cancer after being affected by the failure of the breast cancer screening programme. By offering all women who were not offered their last screening the opportunity to have their final screen it provides the opportunity to detect previously unidentified cancers.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","140669 ; 140670","2018-05-09T15:05:49.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896434/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896434/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-02","Breast Cancer: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to his Oral Statement of 2 May 2018, Breast Cancer Screening, what the timetable is for his Department to contact in writing, the 309,000 women affected by the failure of the breast cancer screening programme.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","140668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896435","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-05-10","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy has undertaken two leak enquiries in the past two years.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-05-10T14:37:32.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896435/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896435/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-02","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many leak enquiries his Department has undertaken in the last two years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","140580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896436","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-05-14","<p>It has been the policy of successive Governments not to comment on security matters other than in exceptional circumstances when it is in the public interest to do so. The leak of any Government information or material is not acceptable and the Government takes such incidents very seriously.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-05-14T17:03:04.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896436/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896436/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-05-02","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many leak enquiries his Department has undertaken in the last two years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","140581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896437","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-05-14","<p>My Department takes the view that any leak of Government information is a serious matter and, along with the rest of Government, takes such incidents very seriously. We do not comment on individual security matters other than in exceptional circumstances when it is in the public interest to do so.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-05-14T16:27:00.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896437/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896437/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-02","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many leak enquiries his Department has undertaken in the last two years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","140582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896438","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-09","<p>Public Health England will contact all the women affected living within the United Kingdom who are registered with a general practitioner before the end of May with the first 65,000 letters going out last week. All reasonable efforts will be made to find the remainder who have moved from England. Any woman who thinks she may be affected has access to a helpline through which they can get access to clinical advice to help them decide whether or not a screening is appropriate for their particular situation.</p><p> </p><p>Data on the number of women affected will be published by the end of May.</p><p> </p><p>There has been no modelling done on the number of women estimated to have undetected breast cancer after being affected by the failure of the breast cancer screening programme. By offering all women who were not offered their last screening the opportunity to have their final screen it provides the opportunity to detect previously unidentified cancers.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","140668 ; 140670","2018-05-09T15:05:49.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896438/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896438/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-02","Breast Cancer: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to his Oral Statement of 2 May 2018, Breast Cancer Screening, how many women have been affected by the breast screening programme failure in each clinical commissioning group area.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","140669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896439","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-15","<p>The leak of any Government information or material is not acceptable and the Government takes such incidents very seriously.</p><p> </p><p>It has been the policy of successive Governments not to comment on security matters other than in exceptional circumstances when it is in the public interest to do so.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-15T15:41:37.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896439/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896439/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-02","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many leak enquiries his Department has undertaken in the last two years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","140583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896440","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-05-11","<p>The leak of any Government information or material is not acceptable and the Government takes such incidents very seriously.</p><p> </p><p>It has been the policy of successive Governments not to comment on security matters other than in exceptional circumstances when it is in the public interest to do so.</p>","Fareham","Suella Braverman",,"2018-05-11T09:58:34.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896440/answer","Biography information for Suella Braverman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896440/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-05-02","Department for Exiting the European Union: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many leak enquiries his Department has undertaken in the last two years.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","140584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896441","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-14","<p>Such an assessment has not been undertaken. The Government recognises that a range of both rapid and slower chargepoints are needed in different locations to meet various charging needs and user behaviour.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-05-14T14:24:46.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896441/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896441/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/896441/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-02","Electric Vehicles: Charging Points","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential merits of up-grading charging points for electric vehicles from slow charge to rapid charge.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","140857"
